that it consists of a horizontal part called the body (A) and a vertical part called the ramus     (B). Note that these meet at the angle (C) of the mandible. Observe that the ramus ends superiorly in the coronoid     process (D) anteriorly, which is where the temporalis muscle attaches, and the condyloid     process (E), posteriorly. The condyloid process consists of the head (F) and the neck (G). The head articulates with the mandibular fossa of the temporal bone at the temporomandibular joint.
The facial bones surround and support the oral cavity, nasal cavity, and orbits.
